XLV. The saripha growing on the banks of the Nile also belongs to the shrub class. It is about 3 ft. high and the thickness of a man's thumb; its foliage is that of the papyrus, and it is chewed in a similar §72- manner. The root is highly rated in workshops for use as fuel, because of its hardness.

XLVI. Also we must not leave out a plant ὁ that at Babylon is grown on thorn-bushes, because it will not live anywhere else—j ust as mistletoe grows on treeS, but the plant in question will only grow on what is called the ‘ royal thorn.' It is a remarkable fact that it buds on the same day as it has been planted— this is done just at the rising of the Dogstar—and it very quickly takes possession of the whole of the tree. It is used in making spiced wine, and is cultivated for that purpose. This thorn also grows on the Long Walls at Athens.
